Every frontend developer has a set of layout patterns they reach for again and again. Here are the ones I use most, using modern CSS Grid and Flexbox — no frameworks needed.
## 1. The Perfect Centering
The classic interview question, now trivially solved:
```css
.center {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```
That's it. Three lines. Works for any content, any size.
Alternatively with Flexbox:
```css
.center {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```
## 2. Sidebar Layout
A layout where the sidebar has a fixed width and the main content takes the rest:
```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```
Want the sidebar to collapse on small screens?
```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .layout {
    grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
  }
}
```
## 3. Responsive Card Grid
This is probably the pattern I use the most. Cards that automatically fill the available space:
```css
.card-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr));
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
```
Breaking this down:
- `auto-fill` — creates as many columns as will fit
- `minmax(300px, 1fr)` — each column is at least 300px, but grows to fill space
- `gap` — consistent spacing between cards
No media queries needed. The grid handles responsiveness automatically.
## 4. Holy Grail Layout
The classic header, footer, sidebar, and main content layout:
```css
.holy-grail {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr 200px;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header  header  header"
    "sidebar main   aside"
    "footer  footer  footer";
  min-height: 100vh;
}

.header  { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main    { grid-area: main; }
.aside   { grid-area: aside; }
.footer  { grid-area: footer; }
```
Making it responsive:
```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .holy-grail {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    grid-template-areas:
      "header"
      "main"
      "sidebar"
      "aside"
      "footer";
  }
}
```
## 5. Auto-fit vs Auto-fill
These two are often confused. The difference matters when you have few items:
```css
/* auto-fill: creates empty tracks to fill the row */
.auto-fill {
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
}

/* auto-fit: collapses empty tracks, items stretch */
.auto-fit {
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
}
```
- **auto-fill** — maintains the column width; extra space remains empty
- **auto-fit** — items stretch to fill the entire row
With 3 items in a container that fits 5 columns:
- `auto-fill` — 3 items at 200px, 2 empty column tracks
- `auto-fit` — 3 items stretched across the full width
Most of the time, `auto-fill` is what you want for card grids.
## 6. Stack Layout
A simple vertical stack with consistent spacing between children:
```css
.stack {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 1rem;
}
```
This replaced the old "lobotomized owl" selector (`* + *`) for adding spacing between elements. The `gap` property works in both Flexbox and Grid.
## 7. Sticky Footer
A footer that stays at the bottom even when content is short:
```css
body {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

/* header is auto, main is 1fr (takes remaining space), footer is auto */
```
With Flexbox:
```css
body {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

main {
  flex: 1;
}
```
---
These patterns cover the vast majority of layout needs. The key takeaway: CSS Grid for 2D layouts and page-level structure, Flexbox for 1D alignment and component-level layouts. Combined with `gap`, `minmax()`, and `auto-fill`, you can build responsive layouts without a single media query.
